The paper deals with the dot-depth hierarchy, which is a well-known concept in formal language theory and automata theory. Therefore, cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the quantifier alternation hierarchy of first-order logic, which falls under cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The paper presents an algorithm, which involves data structures and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses concatenation hierarchies, which are related to computational complexity, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves information theory, as it discusses the decidable levels of the hierarchy, making cs.IT (Information Theory) a possible sub-category.
